The Route Availability (RA) measure used by Network Rail defines the maximum axle weight of services that can be conveyed over any given route. RA ratings are primarily determined by the strength of underline bridges. Rolling stock is also allocated an RA (again between 1 and 10) and the RA of a train is the highest RA of any of its elements. The train must have a route availability (RA) lower than or equal to the RA of a line to be allowed to use it. The RA is primarily related to the axle load of the vehicle, although axle spacing is also taken into consideration. GE/RT8006 Interface between Rail Vehicle Weights and Underline Bridges defines the standards for managing the risk of overloading of underline bridges by rail vehicles.

There are multiple ways in which running lines are distinguished in the UK. The mechanism most commonly used on the operational sphere is radial track descriptions. In UK, railway directions are usually described as up and down, with up being towards a major location. On most of the network, "up" is the direction towards London. In most of Scotland, with the exception of the West and East Coast Main Lines, "up" is towards Edinburgh. The Valley Lines network around Cardiff has its own peculiar usage, relating to the original meaning of traveling "up" and "down" the valley. On the former Midland Railway "up" was towards Derby. On the Northern Ireland Railways network, "up" generally means toward Belfast (the specific "zero" milepost varying from line to line); except for cross-border services to Dublin, where Belfast is "down". Mileposts normally increase in the "down" direction, but there are exceptions, such as the Trowbridge line between Bathampton Junction and Hawkeridge Junction, where mileage increases in the "up" direction. Individual tracks will have their own names, such as Up Main or Down Loop. These radial track descriptions are shown and used as references in the Sectional Appendix. They are also used when specifying the running lines relevant to a possession. Within the engineering sphere, Track IDs are used to differentiate the running lines. These are a 4 digit code, in the format DNXX where:-
  • D denotes the Normal Direction:
    1. Up
    2. Down
    3. Bi-Directional
    4. A Merry Go Round Loop (MGR Loop)
  • N is the Track Name:
    1. Main or Fast
    2. Relief, Slow or Through
    3. Goods
    4. Single Line
    5. Loop
    6. A Terminal Track or Bay Line
    7. A Crossover
    8. Other
    9. A Siding
  • XX is most commonly 00, but where two Lines at the same location would otherwise have the same number, then the second one becomes 01.
